<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,402,571]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Members of this subgenus have: median mesosternal fovea present, body moderately to finely punctate, median antebasal pronotal fovea larger, ranging from same width to about two-thirds width of lateral foveae; males with antennomeres of antennal club simple, abdominal tergites 
<number box="[799,841,475,499]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
often obviously modified, those with simpler tergites have transverse carina or spine at base of tergite 
<number box="[708,724,511,535]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2.0">2</number>
, one species (
<taxonomicName box="[884,997,511,535]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Bryaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="infinita">
<emphasis box="[884,997,511,535]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">B. infinita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) without tergal modifications. Species present over much of North 
<collectingCountry box="[467,563,546,571]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">America</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[720,809,546,571]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
